## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern with **ThreadAbortException as control flow**:

| API | Line | Issue on .NET 8 |
|-----|------|-----------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | after `Join` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | inner try | Never thrown — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | inner catch | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        T result = default;
        Exception error = null;

        var thread = new Thread(() =>
        {
            try { result = work(); }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) { /* cancelled — let thread exit */ }
            catch (Exception ex) { error = ex; }
        });

        thread.Start();

        if (!thread.Join(timeout))
        {
            cts.Cancel();
            // Give the thread a grace period to respond to cancellation
            if (!thread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread is stuck in uncooperative code — it will leak.
                // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in .NET 8.
            }

            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        if (error != null)
            throw new AggregateException(error);

        return result;
    }
}
```

### Better approach — use `Task`-based timeout

The thread-based version has a fundamental problem: if `work()` doesn't cooperate, you **cannot** force-stop it. The modern idiomatic pattern:

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Async variant (preferred)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Caller migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveCalculation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must accept and check the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    token =>
    {
        for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
            DoPartialWork(i);
        }
        return ComputeFinalResult();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation is not automatic** | `CancellationToken` won't interrupt `work()` unless it checks `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular intervals. This is the biggest behavioral difference from `Thread.Abort`. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep(ms)` won't wake up. Use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` instead. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking it causes timer leaks. Always `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Let it propagate; only catch at the orchestration boundary (as shown above). |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If `work()` calls third-party code that can't accept a token, the thread/task **will leak**. The only .NET 8 option is moving it to a child `Process` and calling `Process.Kill()`. |
